    Alfonso R. Reyes out of network 3rd+ VP Artificial Intelligence Engineering - Energy Division

    3mo
    Andrew Ng before AI, we should start by improving the teaching of math, physics, biology and the other sciences. AI by itself brings no value without the context. What is the process that AI is aiming to revolutionize? What are we suppose to improve or change with AI? Don’t fall on the “for a hammer everything is a nail” paradox. Coding and algorithms is just a little piece of the whole.
    23 Replies 23 Replies on Alfonso R. Reyes’ comment

    Andrew Ng Author Founder of DeepLearning.AI; Managing General Partner of AI Fund; Founder and CEO of Landing AI

    3mo
    One way to improve parts of math education is to use CS to motivate and illustrate math concepts. For example, calculus and linear algebra - and maybe even algebra, and the concept of why we need variables - are more motivating to learn when you see how they help you build learning algorithms and other cool software systems.

    Probably other disciplines too. I'm sure creative teachers will come up with exercises where students can deploy inexpensive IoT sensors and write code to collect environmental data for biology; play around with simulations for physics; and so on. Instead of just learning the Gravity Equation F = Gm_1m_2/r^2, won't it be cool if students could code up a simulation using it and see planets whizzing around each other?

    Just as reading literacy is currently a pillar that supports the teaching of other disciplines, in the future I hope AI and coding will be another pillar. It's important that this is done in a way that adds to, rather than merely distracts from, those other disciplines, but I'm optimistic that if teachers and curriculum designers are given AI tools to add to their portfolio of options, they'll find ways to use it that will help motivate and empower students!

    Israel Niezen
    Israel NiezenIsrael Niezen • 3rd+ • 3rd+ CEO At Factored (AI / ML / Data Engineering). Harvard MBA. Data Science Nerd. Karaoke Rockstar. Weekend Surfer.CEO At Factored (AI / ML / Data Engineering). Harvard MBA. Data Science Nerd. Karaoke Rockstar. Weekend Surfer.
    4mo • Edited • 4mo • Edited •
    Remote work conjures up a lot of absolutist opinions.
    In our experience, remote work has been phenomenally successful. We’ve been a fully remote company since our founding 3.75 years ago, and these are some business metrics supporting our remote-first strategy:

    ·     Raised a modest $2.5M seed in the first 7-8 months
    ·     Achieved product-market fit and profitability by the end of Year 1
    ·     ~4x Revenue growth in Year 2
    ·     ~3x Revenue growth in Year 3
    ·     Going for a double this 4th year so we can stay on that elusive Unicorn growth trend. If the economy doesn’t hit a deeper recession, we should hit our number.
    ·     Our ARR is in the 8 digits and we are growing healthily and self-funding our growth via sustainable revenue and cash-flow generation…not an unhealthy addiction to VC.
    ·     Our employee attrition is currently at 2.4% annually, which is unheard of in tech, and certainly in our sector which is hot as hell (data science, AI, Data Engineering, Analytics).
    ·     Remote work has allowed us to hire the absolute best 205 people across 18 countries (and growing). It’s insanity to limit your talent search to a drivable radius from your office. Brilliant talent exists EVERYWHERE.
    ·     It is also insane to expect people to sit in California traffic for 2-3 hours just for the privilege of partaking in your “brilliant” in-person whiteboard and sticky-note design-thinking sessions.
    ·     In 20 years in tech, and 16 of them at startups, I have NEVER been more productive than now that I work remotely.
    ·     Young parents in our team are able to support their families with a lot more flexibility, without having to sacrifice the work and careers they love. We get testimonials about this frequently. That also expands the pool of talent greatly.
    ·     Moreover, our culture and personal friendships and connections are alive and well and don’t skip a beat because we have people at the center of our business strategy, and we are intentional about building our culture and having fun together. See for yourselves in the attached video and turn the volume up!

    To build great culture and make remote-work productive, companies do need to be intentional about these cultural elements that elicit passion and self-driven productivity from their teammates. That takes a lot of intentional design and tons of work. It’s a lot harder to motivate people from a place of love and self-determination, than from a place of fear and in-office whipping into shape. That is probably why the naysayers want to keep a close eye on their teams in person. Maybe they didn’t hire the right people, or maybe their culture is not as inspiring beyond a physical space. But who am I to opine on how others run their businesses? In the end, let them do their thing and force people to work in the office. I will happily continue hiring the best engineers outside of their zip code.

    #hiring #remotework #futureofwork #team #datascience #dataengineering #ai #analytics

    4mo • Edited • 4mo • Edited •
    🔥 Today we officially launched LangKit, the observability and safety standard for LLMs! 🔥

    Check out the notebook to get started with LangKit: https://lnkd.in/gcWQEn6h

    Using LangKit, you can understand and track the behavior of any LLM by extracting 50+ out-of-the-box telemetry signals to implement:

    🛡️ Guardrails: Control which prompts and responses are appropriate for your LLM application in real time.

    ✅ Evaluations: Validate how your LLM responds to known prompts both continually as well as ad-hoc, to ensure consistency when modifying prompts or changing models.

    🔎 Observability: Observe your prompts and responses at scale by extracting key telemetry data and compare against smart baselines over time.

    Learn how you can identify and mitigate malicious prompts, sensitive data, toxic responses, problematic topics, hallucinations, and jailbreak attempts in any LLM with LangKit!

    Read the article by Michael Nuñez in VentureBeat to learn more: https://bit.ly/42GzFdu

    #ResponsibleAI #LLMs #LLMOps #LLMObservability #MLMonitoring #DataScience #AIGovernance
    WhyLabs launches LangKit to make large language models safe and responsible
